JANUARY 3, 1990

     *  Zinc Corp. of America agreed to pay a $614,000 fine to settle

     *  Zinc Corp. of America agreed to pay a $614,000 fine to settle
allegations by the Occupational Safety and Health Administration that the
company's Palmerton, Pa., metal extracting operations violated OSHA's lead
standard and other safety and health requirements.  Under the agreement
reached last month, the company and the United Steelworkers of America
jointly will conduct a training program on lead hazards for all management
and hourly employees, OSHA said.  The  union will select a physician to
review the medical records of employees who may have been exposed to lead.
The company also must consult and cooperate with the union in revising the
Palmerton plant's respirator program, work practices and engineering
controls to address issues raised in the citations.  The agreement includes
these allegedly "willful" violations:  over-exposures to lead; improper
respirator selections; lack of engineering controls for lead; defective
lead medical monitoring and removal programs; and failure to provide
protective clothing.  The company must correct cited violations by June 30.
OSHA defines a willful violation "as one in which an employer either knew
that a condition constituted a violation or was aware that a hazardous
condition existed and made no reasonable effort to correct it."  OSHA
originally proposed fining Zinc Corp.  $1.9 million last March for 295
alleged willful violations of the lead standard.



