U.S., U.K. agree on JAST terms

     The United Kingdom has signed a Memorandum 
of Understanding for its participation in the DoD's 
Joint Advanced Strike Technology program. 
     The U.K. will put up $200 million under the 
arrangement and participate as a collaborative partner 
for the Concept Demonstration Phase (CDP) of 
JAST. The proposed JAST Short Takeoff and 
Vertical Landing aircraft offers a potential supersonic 
future carrier-borne aircraft to replace the British 
navy's Sea Harrier.
     A draft RFP for the CDP was issued for industry 
comment and the formal RFP will be issued early 
this year. The source selection process will award 
one or more CDP contracts.




